Introduction: Forecasting our Future with Prophet

Every day, we make predictions on what to wear (I can definitely relate!) based on the weather. What if we could predict real-world trends with data? Which is what we will delve into!

Objectives of This Report

Get a sense of CO2 levels over time

Use Prophet to forecast future values

Graph trends

Draw conclusions about long-term trends

1.1 Lets get our data ready!

Before we are able to begin predicting, we must correctly format our data for use in Prophet. The default CO2 dataset available in R provides us with monthly observations from 1959 onward. We will change it to a form that can be interpreted by Prophet.

# Load the required libraries
library(zoo)
## 
## Attaching package: 'zoo'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     as.Date, as.Date.numeric
# Rearrange built-in CO2 dataset to a Prophet-acceptable form
co2_df <- data.frame(
ds = zoo::as.yearmon(time(co2)), # Reshape time into Year-Month form
y <- as.numeric(co2) # Convert values to numeric
)
# Print the first few rows of the dataset
head(co2_df)

1.2 Now lets train The Forecast Model

Now that our dataset is correctly formatted, we can train the forecasting model. What the code does: Loads the prophet package Trains the Prophet model using co2_df Generates a future dataframe (8 months ahead) for predictions Prints out future time periods to confirm structure

# Load required libraries
library(zoo)
library(prophet)
## Loading required package: Rcpp
## Loading required package: rlang
# Convert CO2 dataset into a Prophet-compatible format
co2_df <- data.frame(
  ds = zoo::as.yearmon(time(co2)),  # Convert time to Year-Month format
  y = as.numeric(co2)  # Convert values to numeric
)

# Correct column names
colnames(co2_df) <- c("ds", "y")

# Print structure
str(co2_df)
## 'data.frame':    468 obs. of  2 variables:
##  $ ds: 'yearmon' num  Jan 1959 Feb 1959 Mar 1959 Apr 1959 ...
##  $ y : num  315 316 316 318 318 ...
# Print first few rows
head(co2_df)
##         ds      y
## 1 Jan 1959 315.42
## 2 Feb 1959 316.31
## 3 Mar 1959 316.50
## 4 Apr 1959 317.56
## 5 May 1959 318.13
## 6 Jun 1959 318.00
# Train the Prophet model
m <- prophet(co2_df)
## Disabling weekly seasonality. Run prophet with weekly.seasonality=TRUE to override this.
## Disabling daily seasonality. Run prophet with daily.seasonality=TRUE to override this.
# Create a dataframe for future predictions (8 months ahead)
future <- make_future_dataframe(m, periods = 8, freq = "month")

# Display the first few rows of future dates
head(future)
##           ds
## 1 1959-01-01
## 2 1959-02-01
## 3 1959-03-01
## 4 1959-04-01
## 5 1959-05-01
## 6 1959-06-01

1.3 Lets Visualise the Forecast!

Now that we have been able to train our Prophet model, lets get to visualizing the predicted CO2 levels! This part will make plots to enable us to observe the patterns and trends the model is forecasting.

# Load required libraries
library(zoo)
library(prophet)

# Convert CO2 dataset into a Prophet-compatible format
co2_df <- data.frame(
  ds = zoo::as.yearmon(time(co2)),  # Convert time to Year-Month format
  y = as.numeric(co2)  # Convert values to numeric
)

# Correct column names
colnames(co2_df) <- c("ds", "y")

# Train the Prophet model
model <- prophet(co2_df)
## Disabling weekly seasonality. Run prophet with weekly.seasonality=TRUE to override this.
## Disabling daily seasonality. Run prophet with daily.seasonality=TRUE to override this.
# Create a dataframe for future predictions (8 months ahead)
future <- make_future_dataframe(model, periods = 8, freq = "month")

# Check if future dataframe has data
head(future)
##           ds
## 1 1959-01-01
## 2 1959-02-01
## 3 1959-03-01
## 4 1959-04-01
## 5 1959-05-01
## 6 1959-06-01
# Generate predictions
forecast <- predict(model, future)

# Check if forecast was generated
head(forecast)

1.4 Analyse the Forecast!

The cumulative CO2 concentrations are increasing, showing a trend of increase with time.

The confidence intervals (yhat_lower and yhat_upper) indicate potential variations in forecasts, i.e., there is some uncertainty in the future predictions of the model.

There can be seasonality, where CO2 can increase and decrease in a periodic manner due to annual trends.

The Conclusion

Our journey through CO forecasting with Prophet has been both insightful and eye-opening! By averaging historical CO data dating back to 1959, weve successfully built a predictive model that highlights key trends in atmospheric carbon dioxide levels.

Key Takeaways:

Steady Increase in CO Levels Our forecast reinforces what has been observed for a long time by climate scientistsCO level is increasing steadily over the years. This is corroborated by real observations from NASA and NOAA, highlighting the gravity of climate observation.

Seasonal Trends & Annual Variations Prophet was capable of detecting seasonal variations in CO levels, which could be explained by natural cycles in nature, such as absorption by plants during certain times of the year and increased emissions during winter.

References from NASA

Its not just numbers, its a direct reflection of how our planet is changing. With data science and forecasting models like Prophet, we can use data to support climate change efforts, making data-driven decisions that help mitigate risks, drive solutions, and inform meaningful action. If data can make us predict the future, maybe we can change it.

Website: https://climate.nasa.gov/vital-signs/carbon-dioxide/ NASA measures CO concentration and climate patterns from satellite data. It provides very pleasant visualisations and information about CO trends in the long-run.
